        <section id="personal-information">
          <p>I’m <em>Alex Kern</em>, a software developer and computer science student at UC Berkeley. I taught myself to program in C at nine, Java at eleven, and Ruby at fourteen. I focus on building awesome software in Ruby and JavaScript.</p>

          <p>I’ve interned for <a href="http://www.jpl.nasa.gov/">NASA’s Jet Propulsion Laboratory</a>, working on the <a href="http://mars.jpl.nasa.gov/msl/">Mars Science Laboratory</a> and novel data storage techniques. Before attending Berkeley, I was the lead developer at Artcentric Networks, a Los Angeles web startup. I hack on quite a few open source projects, all of which can be found on <a href="https://github.com/CapnKernul">my GitHub</a>.</p>

          <p>Want to talk? You can find me on <a href="https://twitter.com/CapnKernul">Twitter</a> or <a href="mailto:alex@kernul.com">email me</a>. I respond pretty quickly. Interested in hiring me? Check out my <a href="/files/resume.html">HTML</a> or <a href="/files/resume.pdf">PDF resume</a>.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="projects">
          <h2>Projects</h2>
          <dl>
            <dt><a href="https://github.com/CapnKernul/minitest-reporters">minitest-reporters</a></dt>
            <dd>A small extension for MiniTest that lets you create customizable output formats.</dd>

            <dt><a href="https://github.com/CapnKernul/zeppelin">zeppelin</a></dt>
            <dd>A bare-bones Urban Airship library for Ruby.</dd>

            <dt><a href="https://github.com/CapnKernul/webbed">webbed</a></dt>
            <dd>A complete implementation of the semantic aspects of the HTTP specification in pure Ruby.</dd>
          </dl>
